            <p facs="#facs_46_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>-515¬
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>awakened to it, and then the problem arises. This problem is the problem of where the concept of
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>ought-to-be appears. Now he stands before the moment of self-actualization: either to actualize
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>himself or not to actualize himself. In both cases anciety is in him—in the first case the waiety to lose
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>himself when he actualizes himself; in the second, the anxiety that he loses his possibility, his
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>actualization, if he does NOT actualize it. In both cases it is the waiety of self-loss.
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>Now human reality is self-actualization. All men, in degree and in different forms,
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_46_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>actualize their own 6 potentialities. In all of them, it has happened that out of the dreams inocence,
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>they have jumped into self-actualization. But in TOING so, they are not only fuifilling what they
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>essently are, but also they are ESTRANGED from what they essentially are, and they live in the
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>ambiguity of both sufficient and estrangement. Therefore from the point of view of dreams
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>innocence, of non- Ktaalized innocence the child is the ideaI. From the point of view of
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>ACTUALIXATION, the child is that which has to be left behind.
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>We have both words in the New Testament — which is very interesting. On the one hand the
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>child as idea of innocent confidence, as Jesus says to the Apostles, showing a child in this state.
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>On the other hand, the strong demands of Paul to go BEYOND the childish state and to
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>become nature by self- Ktaalization. This is not a contradiction, but these two elements are both in
               <lb facs="#facs_46_tr_2_tl_11" n="N011"/>childhood and in maturity. The process of maturing is also a process of losing something. But without
            </p>
